# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __le__, __gt__, __ge__ across all 10 asyncio subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 10 classes x 3 methods = 30 rows.
# __le__: false for all 10 — <= protocol not in own __dict__.
# __gt__: false for all 10 — > protocol not in own __dict__.
# __ge__: false for all 10 — >= protocol not in own __dict__.
# All 30 values are false.
# asyncio types are designed for coroutine-based concurrency — their entire
#   API surface is expressed through await, async with, async for, and explicit
#   method calls. The comparison protocol dunders (__le__, __gt__, __ge__)
#   are not overridden in the Python-level __dict__ of any of the 10 types.
# asyncio.Future note: Future inherits ordering behavior from object (which
#   provides no ordering — < raises TypeError). It does not define __le__,
#   __gt__, or __ge__ in its own __dict__ despite having a meaningful state
#   machine (PENDING/RUNNING/CANCELLED/FINISHED).
# asyncio.PriorityQueue note: PriorityQueue orders its stored items but
#   defines no __le__, __gt__, or __ge__ in its own __dict__ — the queue
#   object itself is not ordered, only the items it holds.
# asyncio.Event note: Event manages a boolean flag via set()/clear()/is_set()
#   methods; even though it has a logical boolean state, none of __le__,
#   __gt__, or __ge__ is defined in asyncio.Event.__dict__.
# asyncio.Semaphore/BoundedSemaphore note: the permit counter is encapsulated
#   behind acquire()/release() coroutines; no comparison protocol dunders are
#   defined in their __dict__.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

